% PDD formalized baseline (A1): vocabulary + contract_rules for traceability.

<vocabulary>
normalized email: input stripped of leading/trailing whitespace and lowercased
valid email: satisfies R1–R5 simultaneously after normalization
invalid email: any rule R1–R5 is violated
</vocabulary>

<contract_rules>
R1 - Single at-sign

For every email string after normalization,
the system MUST contain exactly one `@` character.

R2 - Non-empty local part

For every email string after normalization,
the system MUST NOT accept an empty local part before `@`.

R3 - Domain with dot

For every email string after normalization,
the domain part after `@` MUST contain at least one `.` character.

R4 - No consecutive dots

For every email string,
the system MUST NOT contain the substring `..`.

R5 - None input

For every call where `email` is None,
the system MUST raise TypeError with message `email cannot be None`.

R6 - Empty after normalization

For every email that is empty after normalization,
the system MUST return is_valid=false with error_message `Email cannot be empty`.
</contract_rules>

<formalization>
R1:
  level: FORMAL_CANDIDATE
  target: normalized email string
  predicate: exactly one '@' character (count equals 1)
  status: bounded string theory — suitable for Z3 proof tests via pdd test

R2:
  level: FORMAL_CANDIDATE
  target: local part before '@'
  predicate: length(local) > 0
  status: bounded — Z3 can encode non-empty prefix

R3:
  level: FORMAL_CANDIDATE
  target: domain part after '@'
  predicate: domain contains '.'
  status: bounded — Z3 Contains('.', domain)

R4:
  level: FORMAL_CANDIDATE
  target: full email string
  predicate: NOT Contains('..', email)
  status: primary Z3 invariant — forbidden substring

R5:
  level: RUNTIME_TEST_ONLY
  target: None input
  predicate: TypeError — not encodable as finite string theory
  status: unit test only

R6:
  level: RUNTIME_TEST_ONLY
  target: empty after strip
  predicate: observable return value — unit test only
  status: unit test only
</formalization>

<coverage>
R1: test_R1_single_at_sign, test_z3_R1_exactly_one_at_sign
R2: test_R2_local_part_nonempty
R3: test_R3_domain_contains_dot
R4: test_R4_no_consecutive_dots, test_z3_R4_forbidden_consecutive_dots
R5: test_R5_none_raises_type_error
R6: test_R6_empty_after_normalize
</coverage>

% When generating tests with ``pdd test``, classify R1–R4 as FORMAL_CANDIDATE per
% generate_test_LLM.prompt and emit runnable Z3-based proof tests (see baseline/tests/test_email_validator_z3.py).

% Implementation target (generated code is output, not source of truth)

Public API:
- class EmailValidator.validate_email(email: str) -> ValidationResult
- dataclass ValidationResult(is_valid, normalized_email, error_message)
